  "final_answer": "There are 184 matched student pairs where study/AI usage time was nearly the same, but academic impact differed a lot.\n\nWhat seems to explain the differences most often:\n- Age: 163 pairs\n- Purpose of use: 154 pairs\n- AI tool used: 147 pairs\n- City: 143 pairs\n- Satisfaction level: 120 pairs\n- Education level: 118 pairs\n- Gender: 94 pairs\n\nKey takeaway:\n- Similar study time alone does not lead to the same academic outcome.\n- The biggest likely drivers are how students use the tool, which tool they use, and how satisfied/effective they feel with it.\n\nExamples:\n- At 0.8 hours:\n  - Student 1 had a slight decline using ChatGPT for writing.\n  - Student 57 improved using Gemini for writing.\n  - Likely differences: AI tool, city, age.\n\n- At 4.2 hours:\n  - Student 4 improved using ChatGPT for learning.\n  - Student 8 had a slight decline using Grammarly for coding.\n  - Likely differences: purpose, AI tool, age.\n\n- At 2.0 hours:\n  - Student 7 had a slight decline using Copilot for research.\n  - Student 76 improved using Copilot for learning.\n  - Likely differences: purpose, satisfaction level, education level, city, age.\n\nMost plausible explanations:\n- Purpose matters: using AI for learning may help more than using it for coding, writing, or homework in some cases.\n- Tool choice matters: ChatGPT, Gemini, Copilot, and Grammarly may support different tasks with different effectiveness.\n- Satisfaction level may reflect effectiveness: students reporting higher satisfaction may be using the tools more productively.\n- Student background matters: age, education level, and possibly city-related learning environment may shape outcomes.\n\nOverall, students with the same amount of study time can perform very differently because the quality, context, and purpose of their AI-assisted study appear to matter more than time alone.",
